<DOC><DOCNO> DOE1-69-0926 </DOCNO><TEXT>The author discusses how journalism was affected by the bombing of Hiroshima.For a time, the local newspapers were shut down because there were nosupplies and no people to write the stories. He concludes that grassrootsmovements don't interest the press until those with real power beginto notice. Then the story becomes one of politics and moves to page one.The author says the journalism we get is the journalism we deserve. Avibrant democracy will produce a vibrant press that will make the vibrantdemocracy possible.</TEXT></DOC>